          <section id="overview">
            <h2>Overview</h2>
            <p>
              A <strong>neural network</strong> is a parameterized function that maps inputs to outputs through a series of
              learned transformations. A network with L layers computes:
            </p>
            <div class="math-block" style="font-size:0.95rem;">
              f(x) = f<sub>L</sub>(f<sub>L-1</sub>(... f<sub>1</sub>(x; θ<sub>1</sub>) ...; θ<sub>L-1</sub>); θ<sub>L</sub>)
            </div>
            <p>
              where each layer f<sub>i</sub> applies a linear transformation followed by a non-linear
              <strong>activation function</strong> to introduce the capacity for modeling complex patterns.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section id="how-it-works">
            <h2>Forward Pass</h2>
            <p>For a single fully-connected (dense) layer:</p>
            <CodeBlock lang="python" filename="forward_pass.py">{`import numpy as np

def dense_layer(x, W, b, activation='relu'):
    """
    x: input vector (n,)
    W: weight matrix (n, m)
    b: bias vector (m,)
    """
    z = x @ W + b          # Linear transformation
    if activation == 'relu':
        return np.maximum(0, z)   # ReLU activation
    elif activation == 'sigmoid':
        return 1 / (1 + np.exp(-z))
    elif activation == 'softmax':
        e = np.exp(z - z.max())   # numerically stable
        return e / e.sum()
    return z  # linear`}</CodeBlock>

            <h3>Key Activation Functions</h3>
            <div style="overflow-x:auto;">
              <table class="data-table" style="border:1px solid var(--color-border);border-radius:8px;overflow:hidden;">
                <thead>
                  <tr>
                    <th>Function</th>
                    <th>Formula</th>
                    <th>Use Case</th>
                    <th>Issue</th>
                  </tr>
                </thead>
                <tbody>
