                      <td style="font-size:0.82rem;color:var(--color-text-subtle);">{issue}</td>
                    </tr>
                  ))}
                </tbody>
              </table>
            </div>
          </section>

          <section id="training">
            <h2>Training: Gradient Descent</h2>
            <p>
              Training minimises a <strong>loss function</strong> L(θ) using gradient descent.
              The loss measures how wrong the network's predictions are. Common choices:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Cross-entropy loss</strong> — for classification problems</li>
              <li><strong>Mean squared error</strong> — for regression problems</li>
            </ul>
            <CodeBlock lang="python" filename="training_loop.py">{`import torch
import torch.nn as nn

model = nn.Sequential(
    nn.Linear(784, 256),
    nn.ReLU(),
    nn.Dropout(0.2),
    nn.Linear(256, 128),
    nn.ReLU(),
    nn.Linear(128, 10),  # 10 classes
)

optimizer = torch.optim.Adam(model.parameters(), lr=1e-3)
criterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()

for epoch in range(10):
    for X_batch, y_batch in train_loader:
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        logits = model(X_batch)
        loss = criterion(logits, y_batch)
        loss.backward()          # Backprop
        optimizer.step()         # Update weights`}</CodeBlock>

            <Callout type="tip" title="Expert tip">
              Adam optimizer combines momentum and adaptive learning rates. For most tasks, it converges
              faster than plain SGD. Use weight decay (L2 regularization) via <code>AdamW</code> to prevent overfitting.
            </Callout>
          </section>

